  <div class="section small_text" data-anchor="install">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="row">
        <div class="col-12">
          <h4>Installing Engines</h4>
          <p>Use a dedicated computer with at least 2GB RAM and 40GB available disk space.</p>
          <p>The machine should be running a fresh and updated version of Linux
            (<a href="http://www.ubuntu.com/download/server"
                target= "engines_linux">Ubuntu Server 16.04 LTS</a> is recommended).</p>
          <p>Login to your computer and enter...</p>
          <pre class="wrap_line">curl engines.org/install | bash</pre>
          <p>You may need to enter your computer's admin password to start the installation.
            You will be prompted to set a timezone. The installer will take about half an hour to run.</p>
          <p>The URL that you will use to access your
             Engines web interface will appear at the end of the process. Open
             a web browser, enter the URL and complete the setup wizard. You'll then be ready to install applications.</p>

          <h5>Advanced</h5>
          <p>Technical installation instructions, and a guide on how to install on AWS, can be found on the
            <a href="http://tiki.prod.engines.org/tiki-index.php?page=Installation+Overview" target="engines_installation_wiki">Engines wiki installation page</a>.
          </p>
          <h5>Uninstall</h5>
          <pre class="wrap_line">curl engines.org/uninstall | bash</pre>
        </div>
        <div class="col-12">
          &nbsp;
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section contrasting_font_color" data-anchor="technical">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="row">
        <div class="col-12">
          <h4>Technical</h4>
          <p>The Engines System software provides a set of core services,
            including volumes, databases, certificates and backups.</p>
          <p>Engines uses Docker to deploy apps and services within sandboxed
             Linux containers. Software can be installed from source, or using
              pre-built Docker containers.</p>
          <p>When building from source, base images for a range frameworks,
            languages and application architectures are supported,
            including OpenJDK, Apache/PHP, Jetty, Tomcat, Sinatra, Meteor,
            Lua, Node, Python, Rails, RStudio and Base&nbsp;C.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="col-12">
          &nbsp;
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

